title: Restart-resume agent runs indefinitely, blocking session queue drain
---
On daemon restart, the restart-resume prompt fires a full agent turn for any pending session. With large contexts (80k+ tokens) and glm-5 as provider, this turn runs many tool-call iterations (up to max_tool_iterations=10) without producing a final text response. During this time:

1. New inbound messages are queued in memory but cannot drain until the turn ends
2. If another restart happens mid-turn, the queue is wiped (see B336)
3. The restart-resume work is not persisted (turn never completes cleanly), so every restart restarts from the same DB checkpoint and re-runs the same research loop

Observed: session telegram:58495225:58495225 ran the same restart-resume loop 3+ times in a row (434 messages restored each time), investigating B230/GitHub webhooks via shell_exec calls, never concluding. Each restart replays the same loop.

## Contributing factors
- `queued_message_interrupt_token` does not interrupt the agent loop (agent.ml:1711-1712 just calls `loop (iteration + 1)`)
- No mechanism to detect 'agent has been running restart-resume for too long' and abort
- glm-5 struggles with 80k+ token contexts, causing 90-120s per LLM call and timeout cascades

## Fix options
1. Skip restart-resume for sessions where context exceeds a configurable token threshold (they'll timeout anyway)
2. Make the restart-resume prompt explicitly instruct the model to conclude in 1-2 turns maximum
3. Add a restart-resume-specific max_iters cap (e.g. 3 iterations) separate from the normal agent max
4. On `queued_message_interrupt_token`, actually interrupt and complete the turn early with a summary